  "text": "The JCE cryptography provider architecture in OpenJDK (repo: jdk--742e735d) consists of the following key files:\n\n1. **Provider.java** (`src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Provider.java`): Defines the abstract `Provider` class, which is the base class for all JCE security providers. It contains the inner `Service` class that describes a specific algorithm/service offered by a provider.\n\n2. **Security.java** (`src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Security.java`): Defines the `Security` class that manages the list of registered security providers. It provides static methods like `addProvider()`, `insertProviderAt()`, `removeProvider()`, and `getProviders()` to manage providers.\n\n3. **SunJCE.java** (`src/java.base/share/classes/com/sun/crypto/provider/SunJCE.java`): The concrete implementation of the SunJCE provider. It extends `Provider` and registers all the cryptographic services (Cipher, Mac, KeyGenerator, etc.) offered by the SunJCE provider.\n\n4. **Cipher.java** (`src/java.base/share/classes/javax/crypto/Cipher.java`): Defines the `Cipher` class with the `getInstance()` factory method that resolves which provider to use for a given algorithm. It looks up registered providers and delegates to the appropriate provider's `Service` implementation.\n\n5. **java.security** (`src/java.base/share/conf/security/java.security`): The JDK security configuration file that lists the default registered providers (e.g., `security.provider.1=SUN`, `security.provider.2=SunRsaSign`, etc.) and their priority order."
}

